Yes, the garden plan still works for Saturday, and I think starting earlier will make the whole morning easier.

If you bring the small hand rake, I can set out the seed trays before you arrive, and we can label everything as we go.

For the herbs, I would keep basil near the warm side of the fence and move the parsley to the shadier corner so it stays steady through the afternoon.

Also, if Mia wants to stop by, tell her to wear older shoes because the ground near the back patch is still soft from the rain.

I checked the pots in the shed, and there are enough for the tomato starts, but the thyme should probably go into the longer planter box.

After we finish, we can sit on the porch and compare notes on which varieties did well last year.

If the weather shifts, we can still sort tools indoors and map out where each row should go.

That way nothing feels rushed, and we can pick up the actual planting step the next dry day.

AAA

Roadside support information for eligible local drivers

You qualify for a AAA Courtesy Roadside Kit

This notice is being sent because your residency falls within a local eligibility area for the AAA Courtesy Bundle For Licensed Drivers. The roadside kit is provided at no charge to eligible residents, and you will not be billed for the kit.

Review your courtesy kit

The program is intended to help licensed drivers in participating residential areas keep basic roadside items on hand. If you are an eligible resident in the covered region, this package is included through the area-supported program, and no payment is required for eligible recipients.

The kit contents below are arranged for common travel situations and routine vehicle readiness. Availability is based on current program allocation for residents in your area.

Reflective warning triangle

Compact flashlight

Battery set for the light

Jumper cable pack

Tire pressure gauge

Pair of work gloves

First-aid supply pouch

Emergency poncho

Window marking pad and pencil

Hand wipes

Foldable safety vest

Storage organizer case

Thank you for taking a moment to review your local eligibility details. AAA values clear, useful service information for drivers in participating communities.

 

That sounds fine for next week, and I do think meeting on Tuesday will help us sort the project notes without rushing anything.

You asked whether the outline should be short or detailed, and I would send the short version first, then keep the longer page ready in case anyone wants clarification.

For the opening section, I would keep the tone plain and direct, then add the schedule points underneath so nothing gets buried in the paragraph.

Also, if Daniel is joining us, let him know we moved the room choice because the larger space has better lighting in the afternoon.

I can bring the printed drafts, and you can handle the agenda, since your last version already had the sections in a good order.

If there is still time afterward, we should review the calendar and set firm dates for the follow-up tasks.

That would keep the rest of the month more organized, and it saves us from repeating the same discussion later.

Let me know if you want me to send a cleaner draft before Monday.

--_mark._lvkie0oq9zavflppgbgxdg5.Atlas.pzjtapkrhkfsioww
